Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Thanks a lot, Victor.

Patch Set 1:

If you don't have time to review this giant patch, you must focus on these 3 files:

* requirements.txt: bump oslo.utils to 1.6
* glance/common/utils.py: remove the exception_to_str() function
* glance/tests/unit/common/test_utils.py: remove exception_to_str() tests

As I explained in the commit message: this patch was generated by a tool (modified version of sixer). Basically, I replaced "utils.exception_to_str" with "encodeutils.exception_to_unicode", but I took care of imports. Later, I replaced "common_encodeutils" with "encodeutils" in two files, glance.common.utils was imported as the name common_utils and my tool didn't know that.

Patch Set 1:

Upgrading oslo.utils to 1.6 is already part of the regular "Updated from global requirements" patch proposed by the bot:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186114/

The problem is that the gate-glance-requirements check job fails. This job became more strict recently. Maybe the problem comes from the "-e https://..." line in test-requirements-py3.txt which was added to quickly test Glance on Python 3.

This line will go away when a new release of glance_store will include my Python 3 patches.

Patch Set 4:

I'd recommend changing to just passing the exception as the replacement value and letting Python take care of it.

In particular, you can just say:

     _('bad thing happend: %s') % e

Python takes care of mixing different types of strings and will do the right thing for you even if the exception contains a lazy enabled message.

The one exception is debug logs where, if you aren't using LOG.exception(), you should ensure that the message is unicode:

     LOG.debug(u'bad thing happened: %s) % e

I.e, any time you apply _() or _L*() to the message they will return unicode.

Patch Set 4:

James Carey:
> I'd recommend changing to just passing the exception as the replacement value and letting Python take care of it.

It doesn't work in all cases. unicode % exc fails if str(exc) contains bytes not decodable from the default encoding, ASCII on Python 3. exception_to_unicode() has a better heuristic to guess the encoding.

Anyway, if you want to enhance logging, I suggest you to write a different patch.

For example, LOG.warning("..." % {'msg': ...}) can be written LOG.warning("..." , msg=...) to not format the string if the logger is configured to only log at ERROR level and above. The logging module only catchs errors on formatting.

> Python takes care of mixing different types of strings and will do the right thing for you even if the exception contains a lazy enabled message.

Well, in general "it works". Exception are more special, especially exceptions raised by Python. OSError and IOError contain messages from strerror() which is localized and encoded to the locale encoding (on Python 2, on Python 3 it's directly Unicode).
